3. Describing vocabularies across samples and comparing response formats within the 2022 sample

We counted how often each word occured in: 1) the mc responses 2) open text responses sample 1 3) open text responses sample 2

This allowed us to quantify content overlap between the three and explore where they do not overlap.

wcounts <- read.csv('activities_unique_output_SUMMARY.csv',
                 row.names = NULL)
# the loaded file is obtained via the Python script count_unique_activity_words.py

Formatting

wcounts.t <- wcounts[1,-c(1,3,5)] # first row contains total, columns with words can be omitted 
wcounts <- wcounts[-1,] # remove total from overall df

# format each data source on its own
wcounts[, 1:2] %>% rename(word = X, S1_open = X1_open) %>% arrange(desc(S1_open)) -> wcounts.S1open 
wcounts[, 3:4] %>% rename(word = X.1, S2_open = X2_open) %>% arrange(desc(S2_open)) -> wcounts.S2open 
wcounts[, 5:6] %>% rename(word = X.2,  S2_MC = X2_mc) %>% arrange(desc(S2_MC)) -> wcounts.S2mc 

# combine into one df with the right format: 
wcounts <- full_join(wcounts.S1open, wcounts.S2open, by = 'word')
wcounts <- full_join(wcounts, wcounts.S2mc, by = 'word')

act <-  read.csv('activities_sample2.csv',

4.1 Base Categories

These are all the base categories

basecat <- c('studying', 'working',  'sporting', 'walking', 'biking', 
'engaging in a hobby','trip / organised activity', 'watching TV', 
'social media consumption', 'being with another person', 
'something intimate', 'household chores','self-care',
'eating', 'relaxing/nothing', 'sleeping', 'travelling', 'nothing')

I would like to look at how often each category was selected. Currently, the dataset contains one variable with all selected choices, each choice separated by a comma.

Now, I first reformat this so that I have one variable per case category.

act[basecat] <- NA # add new variables, one for each base category
y <- 8 # variable 8 is the first one of the new ones = start value for loop

for (cat in basecat) { # now loop for each base category
  for (row in 1:length(act$activity_mc)){ # through every row 
    if(is.na(str_extract(act[row,5],cat))){ # check if the string contains the category
      act[row,y] <- F                 # label presence or absence in the variable 
    } else{
      act[row,y] <- T
    }
  }
  y <- y+1 # after one category is done, we switch to the next variable
}

4.2 Personalised Categories

To obtain the personalised categories, I filter out all the base category responses + the separation comma and save the remaining part of the string in a new variable

# Define a list of standard categories
base.cat <- c('studying', 'working', 'sporting', 'walking', 'biking', 
              'engaging in a hobby', 'trip / organised activity', 
              'watching TV', 'social media consumption', 
              'being with another person', 'something intimate', 
              'household chores', 'self-care', 'eating', 'relaxing/nothing',
              'relaxing','sleeping', 'travelling', 'nothing')

# Step 1: Split each string by commas and trim whitespace
act<- act %>%
  mutate(activity_list = str_split(act$activity_mc, ",") %>% map(~str_trim(.)))

# Step 2: Filter out the standard categories
act<- act %>%
  mutate(personal.cat = map(activity_list, ~setdiff(.x, base.cat))) %>%
  mutate(personal.cat = map(personal.cat, ~.x[.x != ""]))  # Remove empty elements

# Step 3: Filter out rows where personal.cat is empty
act.personal <- act %>%
  filter(lengths(personal.cat) > 0) %>% 
  filter(!map_lgl(personal.cat, ~any(. == "-" | is.na(.))))  # Exclude "-" and NA

nrow(act.personal) # number of times personalised categories were used
## [1] 687

Now I identify unique personalised categories and save them as an object which also contains frequencies of use

unnested.act.personal <- act.personal %>%
  select(ppID, personal.cat) %>% 
  unnest(personal.cat)         

summary.act.personal <- unnested.act.personal %>%
  group_by(personal.cat) %>%
  summarise(
    frequency = n(),                 # Count the frequency of each custom activity
    participant_ids = paste(unique(ppID), collapse = ",")  # Combine participant IDs into a single string
  )

write_csv(summary.act.personal, "summary.act.personal.csv")
